The triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, totaling 29 percent
A noticeable weakening of both parties in the previous grand coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties brought, after the first preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections of Sunday in Austria.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly severe losses, where the position of former chairman Wilhelm Molterer is seriously on the verge.
In contrast, the electoral leader of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the Carinthian Governor Jörg Haider, is preparing for a triumphant return to federal politics.
According to the results so far, social democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest force in the country with 29.8 percent of the votes, but it loses 5.5 percent of the votes compared to the last elections in 2006.
Even worse, the ÖVP, which loses almost nine percent of the votes with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in the post-war history of Austria, and especially in the People's Party, which demanded the early elections, this is a truly catastrophic result.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP had quit the coalition, the People's Party had a clear lead over the SPÖ.
The voters, however, probably punished the party for letting the government fail.
Already in the initial reactions to the results, there were speculations about the possible resignation of the party chairman and former vice chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could already be the case on Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party board.
Such a development would probably pave the way for the most likely way out of the election debacle, i.e. a renewal of the great coalition of SPÖ and ÖVP.
In view of the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ) for the time being received 18 per cent, the BZÖ eleven per cent of the votes - the Social Democrats expressed their fear that 1999 could be repeated when the People's Party had reached agreements with the populists (then the FPÖ was still uniform, in 2005 it split from the BZÖ) with regard to a common government, which had even caused sanctions on the part of the European Union.
Jörg Haider, who has already stated that he is willing to cooperate with each party, obviously relies on this development and assumes a return to Vienna to Austrian federal politics.
The Green Party also moved into parliament, but suffered slight losses and slipped from third to fifth among the Austrian political parties.
No other party has probably mastered the four-percent hurdle and therefore did not join Parliament.
