Turkey expands its diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey sought to join the European Union, the European powers were interested in entering deep into the hinterland of Turkey.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps within Asia, is one of the finest relics of this failed imperial endeavor.
The Hydarpasha station was designed by the two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the guides tell you.
The building sits riddling at the end of the platforms with a tower at each corner of the front and looks like some provincial German town hall.
The rock is dirty.
The whole building is disintegrating about
But once you're inside the arched ticket desk, there's no doubt about the grandeur of the project, the most western access this was.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Bagdad Society.
Germany, which was a late-flyer in the imperialist game, had before its ambitions to dominate the Middle East, by means of a train connection to Damascus, Baghdad, and further beyond what Saudi Arabia is today.
But during the First World War Germany's imperialist plans were framed.
His railroad tracks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arabs.
The relative isolation from its surrounding region, generated by the insurmountable borders of the cold war, has disappeared.
British forces moved out of Egypt and urged the Turks and their German allies from Palestine and Syria
And there was also bad news for the Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, an ammunition train flew into the air, destroying the artistic roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly decayed, gone far beyond history.
Today, however, this railway line, at least symbolically, serves as a gateway to Anatolia and everything east of it to highlight the extension of the diplomatic horizon of Turkey.
The ruling judicial and development party, the AKP, has introduced a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the neighbouring regions, generated by the borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
Now there is a policy of rapprochement.
Remarkably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iran and Iraq and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to be able to assess the key figures of this new foreign policy, I have boarded the night train to the Turkish capital Ankara to visit one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, the Turkish MEP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, about ten and a half hours later, after a bumpy ride on tracks that produced the same step of the old world in the well-known documentary "The Night Mail," I arrived in the Turkish capital, which is regarded as a new city, for the new secular state project to turn its back on the Ottoman past.
But the AKP, known for its Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in Turkish unity
This has caused a lot of distrust in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi took me to the AKP headquarters, a specially designed ultra-modern stone and steel construction, in a developing suburb surrounded by semi-finished shopping malls and pubs where middle managers met in suits, both men and women, to complete the first business of the day.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician of almost any other political party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he even grabbed a Blackberry.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey with its immediate neighbours.
The Cold War was an exceptional phenomenon," he tells me.
Turkey had been cut off from its hinterland.
Today she has to look east and west at the same time.
There wouldn't be either one or the other.
She'd have to do both.
"But certainly Turkey could eventually," I asked, "be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he said, "would not have to face up to this decision."
He then highlighted a point that almost everyone I spoke to almost routinely said: Turkey's relations, not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, are just as beneficial for Europe and the United States as they are for Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, in a figurative sense, Europe as a whole can travel east to Asia and the Middle East on the same railroad tracks.
Back at Hydarpasha's station, after another largely sleepless night, I thought of these two German lords, Mr. Ritter and Mr. Conu, who had been watching this building build 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East could now, to a large extent, be in Turkey's hands.
And when I was waiting at the dock for the ferry to take me back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe" in those days.
At the time, at least, there did not seem to be much doubt as to which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
In memory of Vernon Handley and William Woodruff.
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's musical director since 1962 Vernon "Death" Handley (obituary on September 11) was responsible for the Guildford Philharmonic and Choir.
As part of his music program for the city, he founded his great youth choir, Proteus the following year.
He was meant for young people up to 21 years old, but when the choir sang for the last time in 1979 some of us were already at the end of 20 - we simply refused to leave the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological changer) stood for the willingness and ability of the choir to tackle any piece of music presented to it, whether it was a madrigal or from the Messiah, whether it was a capella or full orchestra.
The musical versatility of such a young chore was often astonishing, always exciting and existed only thanks to the inspiration of that man and his enthusiasm for the music that never left behind for years.
How often did death stop us from "letting music speak for itself."
He used to say, "The composer knows what he wants."
It's all in the music.
So sing it!"
His manner of conducting was absolutely clear and precise, never gorgeous but never overflowing.
However high the musical level was, he always demanded an even higher level.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor should have been beaten to the knight, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the last two decades, from 1962 to 1982, in which he led the Guildford Philharmonic.
In the last 40 years or so, I've written reviews for over a hundred of his concerts and I can honestly say that I've never been disappointed by a single one - I've often been inspired by them.
Death Handley was that rare combination of greatness and personal modesty.
According to his words, he loathed the conductors "with one or two well-known showhorses in the world."
So many of us will miss him.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
In your obituary for William Woodruff (25 September), you write that "he resumed teaching economic history in Oxford in 1946 and received a Houblon-Norman research scholarship in 1950... while at the same time studying for a BSc, a MA and a doctorate.
This is a conclusion from an author's remark in Woodruff's book "Beyond Nab End," but it's not true.
From 1946 to 1953 he was a lecturer in economic history at the University of Nottingham and during this time he wrote a doctoral thesis on the British rubber industry under the supervision of Professor J.D. Chambers, which was later published in 1958 as "The British Rubber Industry."
He was in the United States from 1950 to 1951 in the course of a Houblon-Norman scholarship, and spent the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, Harvard and New York.
In 1953 he finally left Nottingham and went to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff wanted to cover up this part of his career.
