'Car bee' that avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired by nature this time, more precisely, by the bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot whose flight dates back to the swarming behaviour of bees and avoids accidents.
This robot is a Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C and represents the first step in the technologies for accident prevention.
The engineers from the technical development center of Nissan Motor Co. have developed this small robot in cooperation with Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the renowned University of Tokyo (Japan).
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Head of Technology PR and R&D Brand Management, the BR23C represents an extension of the four-layer Nissan security shield.
This robot is designed to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid collisions.
During the flight, each bee builds its own oval-shaped flight room, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the facets of the bee, which can see at an angle of 300 degrees in all directions, which allows her to fly undisturbed in her personal airspace without interruption.
The technicians developed the so-called Laser Range Finder (LRF) in order to recreate the all-round perspective.
He notices obstacles located in front of the BR23C at a distance of up to two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an in-vehicle microprocessor, which is directly translated into signal to avoid the collision
'In the moment that obstacle is noticed, the small robot will imitate the bee flight and immediately change direction by turning his wheels around 90o or even greater angles to avoid collision.
The biggest difference to any other system is that this evasive manoeuvre is absolutely instinctive.
If it were not so, the robot could not be able to react with sufficient speed to avoid obstacles,' explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the senior engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot can't deviate up or down, but it can't move over; it can only move on two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to rotate its wheels, not in the infinite directions and in an infinite way, as the bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used the rotation function in addition to acceleration and braking functions, so that the small robot avoids collisions.
'This device only takes a few seconds to process the information and to act on it.
It does not require to store neither the information nor the intuitive logic of the maneuvers made, therefore it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB of the storage space.
That sounds surprising, but it's not about the GBs and not even the MBs of the storage space.
This is the first step in the development of technologies for the immediate prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan predicts to introduce in the next ten years in the series cars.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than variety of lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system by satellite, in order to lead to the goal while driving while avoiding the obstacles along the way.
