Morgan Stanley provides its capital to MUFG
Morgan Stanley announced Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG)'s entry into its business, which would be the first bank in Japan to spend nine billion dollars and thus take over 21% of its capital, an innovation due to a strong fall in its stock market price.
One week after a preliminary agreement had been made public, the two banks stated that MUFG will buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley common shares at a uniform price of $25.25, representing a total of $3 billion.
The price assumed is less than 19% of the share price of 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional six billion dollars in the acquisition of convertible shares, which will secure a profit of 10% and can be resold at a price of 31,25 dollars.
Morgan Stanley stated that the global business will be made on the basis of a uniform average price of 29 dollars, i.e. 28% above the current price value.
However, the Morgan Stanley share declined by 6.79% to 23.07 dollars at 17.00 GMT.
"This strategic link is an important opportunity to accelerate the transition from Morgan Stanley to holding bank status," said John Mack, Director General of the American Group.
Morgan Stanley accepted this status last week, which will allow him to expand his business to new areas, but under the supervision of the Federal Reserve.
Their connection with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis forces Wall Street's biggest names to adopt a much more cautious stance than before.
The modalities presented on Monday also show that the agreement has changed over the last few days: Last Monday, Morgan had simply declared that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to Japan for about $8.5 billion.
'A week ago', in Tokyo, Toshihide Mizuno, Managing Director of MUFG, said, 'we thought the stake would consist entirely of common shares.
But in view of the current economic and market situation, we wanted to reduce the risks and secure ourselves.'
Based on a balanced average price, MUFG will pay 7% below its price for its Morgan Stanley shares.
And the business will take place with a reduction in profit of about 20% per share.
The agreement provides that in one year, MUFG will be able to convert half of its preference shares into common shares if the latter are exchanged at more than 50% above the selling value within a given period, i.e. at approximately 47 dollars.
Morgan Stanley assures that the funds provided by MUFG will enable him to make use of investment opportunities, strengthen his balance sheet and increase his sales.
However, one of the group's spokespersons refused to provide more detailed information on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After MUFG's investment, Morgan Stanley should be able to record a solvency ratio of about 15%, one of the best in this sector.
Morgan stated that he had 'clearly' lowered his balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks were hard for the group, who had to watch their stock market price fall by half, while the price of insurance against insolvency rose.
This price went down on Monday, but remained at a high level, at about 12%.
Goldman Sachs, the only other 'survivors' of the major investment banks on Wall Street after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the purchase of Merrill Lynch, announced last week that he had taken 15 billion dollars, partly from Berkshire Hathaway, the Warren Buffett group.
Rafael Correa this Monday in Quito.
Refound the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Equatorian Rafael Correa.
It was that third party who this Sunday, following the example of his like-minded and friends, put the plan of a new constitution to the vote.
According to the public results of 80% of the vote, 64% voted 'yes' in the referendum.
According to these results, 28% voted 'no', 7% of the ballots were invalid and 0.7% were left empty.
In order for the constitutional project to be adopted, more than half of the votes cast must be cast.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the polling stations and a census of a non-governmental organisation had announced a clear victory for 'yes' and predicted it to be 63% to 70%.
In the night from Sunday to Monday Rafael Correa, by the way, had demanded the victory of his constitutional project.
The 'constitution has triumphed in an overwhelming way', he had assured Guayaquil, the seat of the government 280 kilometers southwest of Quito, and congratulated the Equatorians.
Of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales, but also by his Chilean like-minded Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which was held in silence according to the observational order of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text consisting of 444 points to secure the 'new socialism' for which the President is committed.
The constitutional project transfers state power to the economy by leaving it with the sole right to 'development planning' in a country that largely lives from oil production by foreign companies and foreign currency, which sends emigrants to the country.
The project, promoted by the Correa elected in 2006, also grants the Head of State greater power, which will be able to exercise up to two successive mandates of four years each, and will have the opportunity to dissolve the National Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will make use of this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also guarantees the principle of free medical care and education, which the President has already begun to introduce in this country, with 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
In the end, it also provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington to use an Equatorian base as a base for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were liberated in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the attack on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions, who had been captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions, who were held in the desert for eleven days, were brought back to the Egyptian capital this Monday afternoon healthy and unharmed.
In the morning, they had been liberated from an Egyptian command in Chad.
Apparently in good condition, the hostages arrived at the Al-Maza military base right next to the Cairo International Airport at about 3.30 p.m. on board a special aircraft.
They were taken directly, without being able to speak to the press, on board a helicopter to the Maadi hospital, a foreign quarter of Cairo, to be examined there.
They all enjoy 'best health' and the kidnappers 'no ransom was paid', said Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna on the runway.
After being captured on September 19 at a SUV safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border area of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, the group of hostages was repeatedly taken from one hiding place by 35 unknown hijackers.
There are eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and also eight Egyptians: two leaders, four chauffeurs, one border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptus, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security officer explained that 30 members of the Special Forces, on board two helicopters, launched the attack at night, just before dawn.
'On both sides shots were shot and half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled,' said this person in charge who wants to remain anonymous.
He explained that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian Special Forces had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of the Italian diplomats Franco Frattini reported from Belgrade, where he is now, on the role that secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces have played.
'We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and performance of our men from the intelligence and special forces', he explained without further details.
He also denied that a ransom had been paid.
On the evening before, the Sudanese army had claimed to have stopped an off-road vehicle in a patrol where the kidnappers were, of which they killed six, including the leader from Chad, and two arrests.
The army declared that they were in contact with a rebel group from Darfur, the Libération du Soudan-Unité (SLA-U), which, however, immediately denied this movement.
Letters - The silent majority of culture
A debate on the financing of culture makes headlines and is the central theme of the current election campaign.
All the better.
But one area of our cultural life remains forgotten.
Who will stand up and denounce the miserable sums that are granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical places that are miserably starving?
What politician will dare to remind the Federal Government that it is neglecting its monuments and its culturally important buildings?
That there are no real laws in Quebec, as in Canada, that effectively protect our cultural heritage?
Did you know that the French government is providing 3.5 million euros for the restoration of Chinon Castle in the Loire Valley alone?
With our American neighbours, it is written in their country's constitution that the protection of cultural heritage belongs to the American culture and that this cultural heritage must be protected by all citizens, all Members and all government districts, in mutual consultation.
In Quebec, in the Association of the Historical Societies of Quebec, at least 40,000 volunteers gathered in 211 historical societies strive to deal intensively with history, to save the numerous private archives with a few pennies, and to preserve the archaeological remains.
They are also often the watchdogs of our cultural heritage who protest with the power of despair when supporters and decision makers release their bulldozers on our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When will there be a stage for history and cultural heritage?
Benelux governments nationalize parts of Fortis Bank
With a partial nationalization, the Benelux countries want to help the Belgian-Dutch Fortis Bank, which is in turmoil as a result of the US financial crisis: The three states make a total of EUR 11.2 billion available to the banking and insurance institute, which also has branches in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands discussed this weekend at the highest level, together with the President of the European Central Bank and the Commissioner of the European Commission's competition authority.
In the eurozone, Fortis is the first victim of the international financial crisis that has been going on for a year, so decisions that are now being made in connection with the bank could have a precedent.
In line with the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states buy the respective shares of the bank at about 49 percent.
The bank is likely to sell part of its stakes, above all the insurance activities purchased by ABN Amro last year.
The shares of Fortis started a steep descent last week, and serious crisis scenarios were already emerging in the second half of the week.
However, analysts agree that the bank, with its 85,000 employees, is far too big for a bankruptcy.
The Institute's securities fell 12% to a 14-year low on Friday.
Since January, the value of the shares has decreased by more than two thirds.
Given the current stock prices, the Group's market value is EUR 14 billion, but this is unrealistic according to management.
The management believes that the USD 700 billion American bailout package and the resulting uncertainty in the markets is to blame for the decline of the Fortis shares.
On Monday, however, the courses rose slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed new Director General of the Bank.
The financial institution was also looking for a private buyer, but there was no interested party with a factual offer.
The Belgian government, however, tried to calm down - no investor should tremble for his money, they said.
So far, no panic has broken out among the customers, the bank's branches have not been stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has its own branches, but it also names leasing companies as its own.
Fox in the henhouse
Because of a person's drug use, life and health insurance in America often refuse to sign a contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear that the data market could become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of the drug data in any case to the consent of the data subject.
These should be in independent hands, otherwise we entrust the chickens to the fox" - quotes the Washington Post Richard Dick, developer of the program for tracking prescription data.
Insurance companies determine the fees and the payment amounts in the event of damage depending on the customer's health, and if the risk is too high, the insurance will not be completed.
In the past, the customer was sent to a medical examination and the contract was concluded only with the knowledge of the results of the examination.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper method: Using the customer's identification number, he obtains the data of the last one and a half years from the pharmacies, i.e., which preparations were purchased, and the program calculates the disease the customer suffers from and how his health is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol lowering drugs, it might be concluded that his blood fat level is untreatable, which would automatically place him in a higher risk group.
There are several versions of the program in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier, so insurance companies only have to do the paperwork more, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the drawbacks is that many medications can be taken for different purposes, such as against migraines and hot flushes, but also against depression.
The latter is a high risk factor from the insurer's point of view, while the ones mentioned above are not.
For the consultation and processing of the data, our own societies have formed, which, before they obtain the data, ask the patient for his consent.
They now have to do this by law, even though omissions have not yet been punished.
Some companies even process the results of laboratory investigations and combine them with the data on drug use. Thus, they provide an even more accurate picture of the patient's state of health.
More and more companies have access to the data and control of their use is becoming more difficult at the same time.
Although there is a separate data protection law for health data, it has an impact only on health service providers and insurance companies.
The draft law has already been submitted to Congress, according to which the authorities could also control the data processing companies.
Dick Richard admits that this is too little, so he wants to develop his program so that the data can only be passed on with the consent of the data subject.
Another question, of course, is that the data subject can hardly prohibit access to his data, since otherwise the insurance companies do not conclude a contract with him.
And so the chickens are left to the Fox's mercy.
Global menu from Marseille
European Union and India double trade
After the European Union and India are each other's leading trading partners, this was the main topic among other global problems at the ninth summit.
Today, too, the French-Indian summit is being held, which mainly discusses cooperation in the nuclear energy sector.
While the European Union recognises that India is an emerging, democratic great power that should be given more voices and voices in international concerns, the member states have not yet been able to agree whether to support the permanent membership of New Delhi in the UN Security Council, or not.
This question was not discussed yesterday at the ninth summit in Marseille.
The French President and current EU President Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Chief Diplomat Javier Solana, received the Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh. An agreement was reached to double trade over the next five years, i.e. increase it to a good EUR 100 billion.
Given that the exchange of goods had increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this objective is not even as ambitious.
In this sense, the 26 existing civil aviation agreements with India have also been legally combined into an agreement, so that aviation will also be encouraged in the future.
By 2009, India wants to sign the free trade agreement with the Union.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the pact.
The aim is to strike a balance between the EU and India: while the Union is the number one partner in India, New Delhi is only 9th among the EU partners.
The summit was devoted to global concerns.
Among them was the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, or terrorism, which both sides strongly condemned. Also the convening of a UN conference was Urged.
The Doha Round should also be completed, with both sides to blame for its failure.
The EU stressed its commitment to its energy and climate programme, i.e. to reduce pollutant emissions by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agreed to this, as did the proposal to conclude a kind of global compromise at the next climate summit and to reduce greenhouse gas production by 50 percent by 2050.
The price increase in food should also be combated, so both support the convening of an international conference on financial crisis.
Today, the Indian Prime Minister visits the French capital, where he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, however, orders to French companies worth EUR 20 billion are hoped for the construction of nuclear reactors in India.
According to agency reports, the agreement is to be adopted for 15 years.
Over 300 Italian publishers in Frankfurt
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the International Frankfurt Book Fair.
More than 300 Italian publishers will be present at the 60th Book Fair, the most important international event for the acquisition of rights.
The international Frankfurt Book Fair awaits more than 7,000 exhibitors from 101 countries for the current event. They will distribute over 171,790 square meters of the fair and present over 403,000 titles. Turkey will be the guest of honor of the event.
The Undersecretary of the Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities Maria Giro will represent the Italian government during the opening ceremony in the exhibition hall: Italy will be represented in the 264 sqm exhibition space "Punto Italia."
This will be followed by a press conference near the Room Structure in the exhibition hall 5.0 of the book fair: on this occasion, figures, trends and perspectives around the publishing industry in Italy will be discussed.
According to the data, the importance of the books of foreign writers decreases throughout the whole, but especially in the adult and youth sectors.
The small aircraft of billionaire Steve Fossett, which disappeared a year ago, was recovered
The small aircraft of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on a flight over the Nevada desert on September 3, 2007, was found.
The items have been found on a high plateau of 3000 m above sea level, in the Sierra Nevada Mammoth Lakes area between the states of California and Nevada.
Inside the aircraft, however, no human remains were found.
The Sheriff of Madera County, John Anderson, completely refuted the last doubts during a press conference: "The plane has been located and a troop has been sent out. Now we have the certainty that it is the plane with which Steve Fossett flew on the day of his disappearance."
Mr. Anderson also confirmed that no human remains were found in or near the plane.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The U.S. Bureau of Traffic Safety (Ntsb) reported that a crew was sent out a few hours after the aircraft was sighted, which identified the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which was lost on September 3, 2007, after Fossett had started a 3-hour flight in Yerington, Nevada.
Yesterday, also in California, near the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal belongings were found by a couple near their home on the Mammoth Lakes.
These are two identity cards named Fossetts, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of illinois, cash and a jacket.
The search for Fossett had been abandoned one month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had conquered a place in history through a long series of records.
In 2002, on his sixth attempt, he was the first person to orbit the world ball in a hot air balloon: a two-week, lonely flight.
Three years later, he flew around the world on a single flight without a stopover by airplane.
Among his several records is also a high-altitude flight of 15445 m above the Andes, which however with a co-pilot.
Glk, the ads you don't expect
